Converting PDF to Data

PDF TO DATA

This tutorial will walk through how to convert PDFs into CSV datasets.
If you already have searchable PDFs and dont want to use Python (i.e. the no code version of this tutorial),
you can skip ahead to Step 3 and stop before the Python section.

- "2. Scanned PDF to Searchable PDF" shows how to take scanned, unsearchable PDFs and make them searchable using Python and Tesseract-OCR. This is a requirement to do Step 3. As Tabula will not work on unsearchable PDFs.

- "3. Searchable PDF to Data" shows how to take searchable PDFs with embedded data in table format and convert them to CSVs that can then be cleaned
and combined in Stata or other statistical software programs.
NOTE: This section can be done with no code, or can be automated using Python.

ScannedPDF_to_Searchable

This notebook will go through an example of converting a folder of scanned pdf's into searchable pdfs.

NOTE: This tutorial assumes your are using Windows.

STEP 1 : Install Tesseract OCR¶

  • The first step will be to install the Tesseract OCR engine on your machine: https://github.com/UB-Mannheim/tesseract/wiki

  • The Tesseract engine will recognize english characters and convert the scanned pdf's into text. Note that the engine is not 100% accurate and accuracy may vary.

  • Select the 32 or 64 bit version based on your windows machine. (To find if your computer is 32 or 64 bit search "System Information" in windows search and look for System Type.

  • NOTE : It is best to install into the predefined folder during instillation. This folder is usually "Programs/Tesseract-OCR"

STEP 2 : Install Python¶

  • The easiest way to install python is through Anaconda:

    • https://www.anaconda.com/products/individual

  • Again choose the 64 or 32 bit windows version depending on your machine

Step 3 : Install Packages in Python¶

For reference see: https://datatofish.com/how-to-install-python-package-in-anaconda/

  • In Windows search bar type : Anaconda Prompt

  • We then need to pip install several packages as show below, make sure each individual package downloads before installing the next one.

  • pip install Pillow
  • pip install pytesseract
  • pip install pdf2image
  • pip install PyPDF2

Step 4.1 : Convert our PDFs¶

To do this we will open "Spyder within Anaconda"

  1. Open Anaconda
  2. Click "Launch" next to Spyder. You should see this IDE load if done correctly:

Step 4.2 : Insert the Code below¶

  • And adjust so the folder paths match your machine

  • You should not need to edit any lines of code after setting the indir, outdir and tesseract_dir

  • Then you just need to hit "Run" in Spyder and you should see a list of files being converted in the console.

#Importing packages similar to R
#NOTE: make sure they are installed! 
from PIL import Image
import pytesseract
from pdf2image import convert_from_path
import os
import PyPDF2
from os import listdir
from os.path import isfile, join

#Set full folder path to folder with scanned PDFs
#include "r" at the begenning and only use forward (/) slashes in between
indir = r"C:/Users/kylem/Desktop/convertPDF/scanned_pdf"

#SEt folder path for output (This should be a seperat folder than the one above)
outdir = r"C:/Users/kylem/Desktop/convertPDF/searchable_pdf"

#Set location of tesseract.exe we just downloaded
tesseract_dir =  r"C:\Program Files\Tesseract-OCR\tesseract.exe"

#This command gets a list of all files in the "indir" folder
# SO make sure this folder only includes the scanned PDFs!
pdfs = [f for f in listdir(indir) if isfile(join(indir, f))]

#SHOULD NOT HAVE TO EDIT ANY CODE BELOW THIS LINE
for pdf in pdfs:
    print(pdf)
    # 1 : Converting each PDF page to images
    # Store all the pages of the PDF in a variable
    os.chdir(indir)
    pages = convert_from_path(pdf)

    # Counter to store images of each page of PDF to image
    image_counter = 1

    # Iterate through all the pages stored above
    for page in pages:
        os.chdir(outdir)
        # remove .pdf extension from filename
        pdfname = pdf.replace(".pdf", "")

        # Declaring filename for each page of PDF as JPG
        filename = str(pdfname)+str(image_counter)+".jpg"

        # Save the image of the page in system
        page.save(filename, 'JPEG')

        # Increment the counter to update filename
        image_counter = image_counter + 1

    # 2 - Recognizing text from the images using OCR
    # Variable to get count of total number of pages
    filelimit = image_counter-1

    # Iterate from 1 to total number of pages
    for i in range(1, filelimit + 1):
        print(i)

        pdfname = pdf.replace(".pdf", "")

        #make file names
        filename_jpg = str(pdfname)+str(i)+".jpg"
        filename_pdf = str(pdfname) + "_" + "pg" + str(i) + ".pdf"
        print(filename_pdf)

        # Convert PDF to searchable PDF to use with Tabula
        pytesseract.pytesseract.tesseract_cmd = tesseract_dir
        pdf_wSText = pytesseract.image_to_pdf_or_hocr(Image.open(filename_jpg), extension='pdf')
        f = open(filename_pdf, 'w+b')
        #!!! NOTE: IF you are getting weird characters in your output you can try to change the encoding
        #          perameter in the line above
        #          An example is such : f = open(filename_pdf, 'w+b', encoding="ascii")
        #           
        #          Common options for english text for encodings are == {ascii, utf_8, utf_16}
        #          A List of all encodings are here : https://docs.python.org/2.4/lib/standard-encodings.html
        #          
        
        f.write(bytearray(pdf_wSText))
        f.close()


    #Make PDF Pages to combine all pages into the original PDF, but searchable.
    mergedpdf = PyPDF2.PdfFileMerger()
    for i in range(1, filelimit + 1):
        filename_pdf = str(pdfname) + "_" + "pg" + str(i) + ".pdf"
        mergedpdf.append(PyPDF2.PdfFileReader(filename_pdf, 'rb'))

    mergedpdf.write(pdf)

Step 5 : Cleanup "Outdir"¶

Once the code runs, in the "outdir" you set, you will have three types of files:

  1. JPEGS of each pdf page (You can delete all JPEGS these were just byproducts of Tesseract)
  2. Individual pages of all PDFs (these have pg. number extensions at the end of the file)
  3. Recombined PDFs that are now searchable. (these dont have page number extensions at the end of the file and should match the scanned pdf exactally but it is now searchable.)

Depending on your PDF it may be easier to select individual pages that have data on them (for example if a 100 page PDF only has data on page 3, only keep that page for the next step).

Or it may be easier to keep the whole pdf and convert all pages together. (For example if we have accounting data tables with the same format on 60 consecutive pages).

So cleanup the outdir to include pages, or full pdfs depdneing on your individual situation, then proceed to step 3!

SearchablePDF_to_Data

This notebook will walkthrough how to convert searchable PDFs into datasets.

STEP 1 : Install Tabula¶

To do this visit : https://tabula.technology/ and download for windows.

Unzip the folder and place it somewhere easy to find.

Then within the unzipped folder double click "tabula.exe" You may need to download or update Java for this to work, it will promt you when you launch.

After launching a internet browser tab should open that looks like below:

STEP 2 : Visualize your PDF to Data conversion¶

While you can run Tabula directly in Python it is very helpful to visualize the data generating process before running script in Python.

To do this load a searchable PDF into Tabula and then hit "Import"

After Import you will see something like below (obviously will look different using different data)

To get best results it is best to highlight only the portions of pages that are tables. You can also right click the selection and add it to all pages if you uploaded a multi page PDF with a similar format on

Below is the table output from Tabula based on my selection above. As you can see Tabula is not perfect and will sometimes place words in columns they should not be.

As of now, I have not found a workaround for this other than either hand editing the results .csv or editing the individual .csv in stata afterword to get the columns to match up.

Two Type of Data.¶

NOTE : There are two types of tables.

For data whos cells are not separated by lines/boxes use the "stream" option.

For data whos cells are separated by lines/boxes use the "lattice" option.

You can stop here if you do not want to automate the process with Python and instead want to convert each PDF (or PDF page) to data by hand. Just repeat the steps above, exporting .csv by .csv and then combine and clean them at the end using Stata.¶

STEP 3 : Automate using Python¶

After you have tried all possible selection option in Tabula and have seen the resulting .csv, find your preferred selections for each page and instead of exporting as .csv select export as script, as shown below:

Then open the exported scrip in notepad or notepad++.

You will see the following :

The numbers highlighted in red are the coordinates of you selection area (The red box with dotted line selection highlighting my whole table in the first image.)

These coordinates will be used in the next step to tell python where on each page to create a table.

We will need to download one more package in Python :

  • pip install tabula

Once tabula package is install open up Spyder again and copy the code below into Spyder Editor.

Pay close attention to the comments in the below code if you have multiple different pages of PDF with different selection boundaries. Also if you have lattice data be sure to change that option and omit the guess option.

NOTE: The Numbers highlighted in red above correspond with the area option below.

import tabula
# Get list of PDF in folder
import os
from os import listdir
from os.path import isfile, join

#This command will turn all searchable pdfs within the folder into datasets.
#It is important you keep similar PDF in seperate folders. 
#If you need to repeat the code below for several folders with different selection boundaries then do so. 
#This will save all .csv into the "searchable_pdf folder"
#NOTE: stream option means no lines are in the tables, guess = false makes stream work, area was found in tabula.io
dir = r"C:/Users/kylem/Desktop/convertPDF/searchable_pdf"
os.chdir(dir)
tabula.convert_into_by_batch(dir, output_format="csv",
                             pages="all",
                             stream=True,
                             guess=False,
                             area=[216.386, 286.818, 1506.216, 2114.077]
                             )
